              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                Both Friedrich Hayek and John Maynard Keynes have written approvingly of Mandeville’s fable. According to Hayek, Adam Smith gained insights into the division of labor, self-interest, economic liberty, and the idea of unintended consequences from Mandeville (Hayek 1984: 184–85). Keynes approved of Mandeville’s anti-saving sentiments and statist pressures to assure full employment in society (Keynes 1973: 358–61).
